<DOC><DOCNO> AP890428-0050 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0558EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WashingtonBicentennial     04-28 0276</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington Bicentennial,0282</SECOND><HEAD>City Plans Big Party For 200th Anniversary Of Washington's Inauguration</HEAD><BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Red, white and blue will be the rage thisweekend as the 200th anniversary of George Washington'sinauguration is celebrated with a flotilla of ships, a fireworksdisplay and a parade led by President Bush.   Washington's swearing-in as the first president was watched bysome 20,000, just 10,000 fewer than the city's population in 1789.More than 2 million are expected to gather to watch thebicentennial events.   The highlight will be the inaugural commemoration at FederalHall on Sunday, marking the moment when Washington put his hand tothe Bible and swore to ``faithfully execute the office of presidentof the United States.''   Bush will speak at the ceremony _ which falls on his 101st dayin office. And a white-haired Philadelphian, William Sommerfield,will play the part of Washington and deliver part of the firstpresident's inaugural address.   The city kicks off the festivities Saturday with a flotilla inNew York Harbor. Thirteen U.S. Navy and Coast Guard shipsrepresenting the original states will be joined by 50 commercialand civilian vessels coming down the Hudson River.   At night, a fireworks spectacular called ``Hail to the Chief,''narrated by Walter Cronkite, will emblazon the sky. Scenes ofpyrotechnics will tell the history of the presidency.   Prior to Sunday's commemoration, Bush and other dignitaries willattend an ecumenical service at St. Paul's Chapel, where Washingtonprayed after his inauguration.   After the ceremony, Bush will lead a parade that will includethe official bands of the Army, Navy, Marines and Air Force.</TEXT></DOC>